​1. Introduction
​The Portfolio of Evidence (PoE) for this Web Development module represents the culmination of our foundational programming and design knowledge, applied to a real-world software engineering challenge. My understanding of this PoE is that it functions as a comprehensive, end-to-end assessment designed to test our ability to architect, build, secure, and deploy a fully dynamic database-driven web application. Rather than relying on modern, abstraction-heavy frameworks like Laravel, React, or Tailwind, the objective of the project was to construct an e-commerce platform using "pure" native PHP, Vanilla JavaScript, and raw SQL queries via MySQLi.
​This constraint forced us to deeply understand server-side state management, session handling, secure role-based routing, database normalization, and defense mechanisms against common web vulnerabilities like SQL Injection and Cross-Site Scripting (XSS). The specific problem space we chose to address was the growing sustainable fashion market in South Africa, leading to the creation of PASTIMES—a specialized peer-to-peer second-hand clothing marketplace. The project required the seamless orchestration of three distinct user environments (Buyer, Seller, and Administrator) interacting with a single, synchronized schema containing complex data dependencies. Ultimately, the PoE served not just as an academic evaluation, but as a simulated professional production pipeline testing our collaborative design, version control, technical problem-solving, and clean-coding principles.
