3. Research, Technology, and the Presentation of Information
​Scenario 1: Implementing Native Asynchronous Interactivity (AJAX Cart & Wishlist)
​The project specification required a seamless, highly reactive user experience where buyers could add items to their cart or wishlist without forcing a disruptive page refresh. Since we were restricted from using external libraries like jQuery or Axios, I had to conduct focused research on native JavaScript asynchronous web APIs.
​I deeply analyzed the modern fetch() API, investigating how to correctly structure asynchronous HTTP requests, set request headers for JSON data payloads, and process the resulting server promises. On the server backend, I researched how to design standalone PHP handler scripts (ajax/cart.php and ajax/wishlist.php) that would intercept these background requests, validate active session tokens, interact with tblCart or tblWishlist, and echo back clean, structured JSON response codes instead of standard HTML blocks.
​This research was critical; it allowed me to successfully implement dynamic frontend DOM updates via JavaScript based on backend MySQL transactions. As a result, the user receives instantaneous, glowing visual feedback when saving a luxury pre-loved jacket, significantly elevating the professionalism of the platform presentation.
​Scenario 2: Secure Password Hashing and Countering SQL Injection
​Another critical research scenario involved ensuring total security across our authentication pipeline. I had to investigate industry-standard methodologies for protecting user credentials and database integrity within a plain, native PHP ecosystem. I researched the cryptographic differences between legacy, insecure algorithms like MD5 or SHA1 and modern adaptive hashing algorithms. This led me to adopt PHP’s native password_hash() utilizing the PASSWORD_DEFAULT flag, which implements robust Bcrypt encryption with automated salting.
​Additionally, I researched defense mechanisms against SQL Injection (SQLi) attacks. I studied the mechanics of how malicious inputs can escape standard query strings and run unauthorized code on the database server. This research guided me to mandate the use of parameterized MySQLi object-oriented statements with explicit type definitions using bind_param() across every database interaction file in the project. Presenting this secure data structure ensured that our login gates were impenetrable to common injection scripts, fulfilling both academic compliance and professional security standards.
